node.text: She is beauty, she is grace. She’s got meat-tube on her face. 😹

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Andrew Marttila on July 16, 2021 tagging @kittenxlady. May be an image of cat.

node.text:
This little dude gave us a real scare last night. I stayed up with him late to make sure he continued to eat and drink, and that he didn’t fade away. With some medical treatment and TLC, he’s looking much more chipper today. Fingers crossed he’s able to combat this infection. 

This is really hard. Every time I look at him I have to hold back tears. I know how this story ends, I just hope there are many more chapters before we get there. ❤️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Andrew Marttila on July 15, 2021 tagging @kittenxlady, @orphankittenclub, and @saratoga_cat_sanctuary. May be an image of 1 person, cat and indoor.

node.text:
My new gf 🥰

She’s got a rotund belly, crunchy meatface, and a huge bald spot on her head. Could she be any more perfect?

node.text:
#sponsored For as much as I take photos of cats, I so rarely take pictures of my own! I was working on a concept of obscuration, initially trying out pictures of my cat in tunnels, blankets, and boxes accompanied by complicated lighting systems from various angles. You name it; I tried it. And if you know cats, you know that capturing them can be tricky, especially if they sense you're hard at work!

Frustrated, I began to pack up my @canonusa #5DMarkIV for the day. At that moment, my cat hopped up on the bed and sat in the one sunbeam shining through the drapes. I finally had the photo I was after. Fortunately, working with @canonusa’s system is unbelievably simple to quickly switch settings to match the environment. All the essential features are literally at your fingertips so that you never miss a golden opportunity. I spun my aperture wheel and modified the shutter speed slightly, and boom!

Working with animals has its own inherent set of difficulties, and sometimes you just have to be patient and let them call the shots.

Settings: Canon 5D Mark IV - Canon EF 35mm f/1.4 II USM - 1/250 at f/3.5, iso 125 @ 35mm 
#5DMarkIV #CanonCreator
